==English==

===Pronunciation===
*{{audio|en-us-seduce.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Etymology===
Borrowed from Latin '''seducere''', from '''se-''' meaning "aside, away, astray" + '''ducere''' meaning "to lead"

===Transitive verb===
'''to seduce'''  (''past tense'' [[seduced]])
#To [[beguile]] or [[lure]] someone [[away]] from [[duty]], [[accept]]ed [[principles]], or [[proper]] [[conduct]]. To lead astray.
#To [[entice]] or [[induce]] someone to [[engage]] in a [[sexual]] [[relationship]]
#To [[win over]] or [[attract]] someone

====Translations====
*French: [[seduire]] (1), (2), (3)
*Italian: [[sedurre]]
*Latin: [[seducere]]
*Spanish: [[seducir]]

===Derived terms===
*[[seduction]]
*[[seductive]]
*[[seducement]]
*[[seductress]]
